{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583085"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:06:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:06:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1976"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1976"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1976"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85589"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1976"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1976"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69881"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"986"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10697"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"804"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85589"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old medical student is studying for their biochemistry examination. They are reviewing the structure and function of nucleic acids, including deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) and ribonucleic acid (RNA). They understand that nucleic acids are composed of nucleotides, each containing a nitrogenous base, a pentose sugar, and a phosphate group. They are now focusing on the classification of the nitrogenous bases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nitrogenous bases is classified as a purine based on its chemical structure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thymine","Cytosine","Uracil","Adenine","Guanine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENitrogenous bases are fundamental components of nucleic acids (DNA and RNA) and can be classified into two main groups based on their chemical structure. \u003Cstrong\u003EAdenine\u003C/strong\u003E is correctly identified as a purine, as it contains a double-ring structure consisting of a six-membered and a five-membered nitrogen-containing ring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThymine\u003C/strong\u003E is a pyrimidine found in DNA, containing only a single six-membered ring. It pairs with adenine through hydrogen bonding in the DNA double helix.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytosine\u003C/strong\u003E is also a pyrimidine, found in both DNA and RNA. It pairs with guanine through hydrogen bonding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUracil\u003C/strong\u003E is a pyrimidine found exclusively in RNA, where it replaces thymine and pairs with adenine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGuanine\u003C/strong\u003E is also a purine, like adenine, containing the characteristic double-ring structure. Understanding the structure and classification of these bases is crucial for comprehending DNA replication, transcription, and various genetic disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Purines (adenine and guanine) have a double-ring structure, while pyrimidines (thymine, cytosine, and uracil) have a single-ring structure.","Adenine pairs with thymine in DNA and with uracil in RNA.","Understanding purine structure is important for comprehending purine metabolism disorders like gout."],"references":["National Center for Biotechnology Information, PubChem Database, accessed 14/4/20, https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69881"}},"question":{"data":{"type":